{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619557"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16562"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16562"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75969"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9253"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7106"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75969"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ventricular system of the brain consists of interconnected fluid-filled chambers that produce and circulate cerebrospinal fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical relationships of the third ventricle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Connected to the fourth ventricle via the foramina of Monro","Located between the cerebellar hemispheres","Contains the choroid plexus in its floor","Separated from the lateral ventricles by the septum pellucidum","Bounded laterally by the thalami and hypothalami"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe third ventricle is a narrow, midline CSF-filled cavity in the brain. \u003Cstrong\u003EBounded laterally by the thalami and hypothalami\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of its anatomical relationships. The third ventricle communicates with the lateral ventricles via the interventricular foramina (of Monro) and with the fourth ventricle via the cerebral aqueduct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnected to the fourth ventricle via the foramina of Monro\u003C/strong\u003E - The foramina of Monro connect the lateral ventricles to the third ventricle, while the cerebral aqueduct connects the third to the fourth ventricle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated between the cerebellar hemispheres\u003C/strong\u003E - The fourth ventricle, not the third, is located between the cerebellar hemispheres\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains the choroid plexus in its floor\u003C/strong\u003E - While the third ventricle does contain choroid plexus, it is located in its roof, not its floor\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeparated from the lateral ventricles by the septum pellucidum\u003C/strong\u003E - The septum pellucidum separates the two lateral ventricles from each other, not from the third ventricle\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding ventricular anatomy is crucial for interpreting neuroimaging studies and managing conditions such as hydrocephalus, where CSF flow or absorption is impaired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The third ventricle is a midline CSF-filled cavity bounded laterally by the thalami and hypothalami.","The cerebral aqueduct connects the third ventricle to the fourth ventricle.","The choroid plexus is located in the roof, not the floor, of the third ventricle."],"references":["Ahmed SI, Javed G, Laghari AA, Bareeqa SB, Aziz K, Khan M, Samar SS, Humera RA, Khan AR, Farooqui MO, Shahbaz A. Third Ventricular Tumors: A Comprehensive Literature Review. Cureus. 2018 Oct 5;10(10):e3417. doi: 10.7759/cureus.3417. PMID: 30542631; PMCID: PMC6284874.","Rhoton AL Jr. The lateral and third ventricles. Neurosurgery. 2002 Oct;51(4 Suppl):S207-71. PMID: 12234450.","Glastonbury CM, Osborn AG, Salzman KL. Masses and malformations of the third ventricle: normal anatomic relationships and differential diagnoses. Radiographics. 2011 Nov-Dec;31(7):1889-905. doi: 10.1148/rg.317115083. PMID: 22084178.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61470"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T19:05:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:05:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9253"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75969"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"